after that mcp also will suport in that llm?

Yes — MCP isn't Claude-exclusive. It's an open protocol, so any LLM that has an MCP-compatible client can use the same servers we just set up (Kubernetes, GitHub, Jenkins).

How this works with Ollama specifically:

Ollama itself doesn't have MCP built in yet, but there are MCP client tools that sit on top of it:


Tool                  What it does
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Continue.dev          Open-source AI coding assistant, supports MCP +
                      local models via Ollama

LibreChat            Open-source ChatGPT-like UI, has MCP support,
                     can point to Ollama as the backend

Custom Python        You write your own client using the MCP Python
script               SDK + call Ollama's API — full control, more work

Practical reality: the same MCP servers you already configured (kubernetes-mcp-server, @modelcontextprotocol/server-github, @kud/mcp-jenkins) would work unchanged — MCP servers don't care which LLM is calling them. You'd just point a different client (LibreChat, Continue, or your own script) at your local Ollama model instead of Claude.

One honest caveat: open-source models (Llama 3, Mistral) are noticeably weaker than Claude at reliably calling tools correctly — tool-use/function-calling was a specific area Claude/GPT-4 class models were heavily trained on. A local 7B/8B model might call the wrong tool, malform arguments, or ignore instructions more often. It'll work, just expect more errors than what you just saw with Claude.

