so this is my own ai?

Sort of — let's be precise about what "own" means here, since it matters:

What IS yours:

• The installation — running entirely on your laptop, no data sent anywhere

• The runtime/environment — you control it completely, can turn it off, delete it, run it offline

• Anything you build on top (RAG with your notes, MCP connections to your Jenkins/K8s/GitHub)

What is NOT yours:

• The model itself (Llama 3) — trained by Meta, using their data, their compute, their training process. You're running a copy of their pre-trained model, not something you built

• You didn't create the "intelligence" — you're hosting/operating an open-source model someone else trained

Accurate way to describe it: it's a privately-run, self-hosted AI assistant — similar to how running Nginx on your own EC2 instance doesn't mean you built a web server from scratch, but you do fully own and control that specific running instance.

If you truly wanted to "build your own AI" — that would mean training a model from scratch on data you choose, which requires the massive compute/cost we discussed earlier (unrealistic solo).

For practical purposes though — yes, this is a legitimate way to have a private, offline, customizable AI assistant that's entirely under your control, and you can absolutely call it "my own local AI setup." Just worth knowing the distinction if it comes up in an interview or technical discussion.
